text:
Writing: Taking a day. Instead of editing a piece the same day I write/finish it, making space to edit the following day.

Strategy: Raising rates consistently and more than you’re comfortable with. I’ve gone from $0.25/word to $1+/word in two years. I haven’t changed my offerings, just my price.

Workflow: This might just be me, but I batch my work into outlining, writing and editing. For some reason I can outline 3 pieces a lot faster than just one. Then when I come to writing it, getting everything down on paper goes a lot faster, too.

text:
A few things come to mind:

For writing...what <@U014RK24F9D> said. Stretching editing and writing over several days. Sleeping on things is magic.

For clients/process...getting approval and feedback on outlines.

For sanity...I'm working on sharing stuff before it's perfect. When I first started, I thought a piece had to be 110% ready-to-go when I shared a draft for review. And while I still (rightfully) sweat over clarity, structure, and grammar, I'm more comfortable getting feedback in earlier stages because it most always makes for a stronger piece.

text: <@U01676BJQ7Q> During the initial research phase now I can usually see where there might be opportunities to update the scope of work. Some of it though is just learning from how you work with a client. I recently had a client who said they initially wanted a longer-form article. Then midway they played around with the idea of it being a series. It ended up being a pillar piece for them and I asked for more the next go-round with them and they agreed because they knew I would over-deliver again.

text: We’ve just been discussing removing our comments section at work. Our blog is about 10 years old with tons of flipped content over time. Most of the quality comments are outdated now and we’ve seen that only about 10% of comments have any value—the rest are spam, rants, or people commenting for a link. We have a pretty active community that will share feedback and discuss on social so maybe be removing comments from the site.

text:
Hi all! In your opinion, what are the key components of a content marketing strategy?

I am (finally) documenting our in-house content marketing strategy for each of our blogs, and have <@UJG9WTEKG>'s articles on content strat at the ready, but am getting some mixed information online when it comes to templates etc.

I'm currently digging into the following:

• aligning our objectives with our key stakeholders
• extracting different data points to help map out our reader personas
• defining our success metrics and how to measure our ROI
• our competition 
• the aim towards a diversifying our content marketing strategy
and would love to hear from you experienced peeps about your process when it comes to crafting your content marketing strategy. We look after both B2B and B2C content.

Still a newbie when it comes to strat, so any feedback is welcome! Cheers
